{
  "doc_id": "20421",
  "text": "Ultrasonography of the pleurae and lungs, including the diaphragm, has been extensively described [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Detection and estimation of the pleural effusion volume using ultrasonography is reproducible and independent of the operator [CITATION_3] . In the presence of pleural effusions, an acoustic window allows physicians to visualize the diaphragm and pleural cavity, thus a more detailed examination may reveal additional lesions. In the absence of free fluid, the phenomenon of a strong reflection of ultrasound waves from air-filled lungs does not allow penetration of ultrasound and imaging of structures deeper than the pleural line. Lung ultrasonography is a good diagnostic strategy to use for a transthoracic biopsy in the diagnosis of subpleural masses that are suspicious of malignancy [CITATION_4] , or to perform safe ultrasound-guided thoracocentesis [CITATION_5] . For patients with advanced EOC, in whom pleural effusions or metastatic disease is suspected, video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery is considered a safe and accurate method for diagnosing metastases in the pleural cavity [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , and it can be planned immediately after lung ultrasonography.",
